'''[[Scientific misconduct]]''' is the violation of the standard codes of [[scholarly method|scholarly conduct]] and [[ethics|ethical behavior]] in the publication of professional [[science|scientific research]]. A ''[[The Lancet|Lancet]]'' review on ''Handling of Scientific Misconduct in Scandinavian countries'' gave examples of policy definitions. In Denmark, scientific misconduct is defined as "intention[al] or gross negligence leading to fabrication of the scientific message or a false credit or emphasis given to a scientist", and in Sweden as "intention[al] distortion of the research process by fabrication of data, text, hypothesis, or methods from another researcher's manuscript form or publication; or distortion of the research process in other ways."<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Nylenna M, Andersen D, Dahlquist G, Sarvas M, Aakvaag A | title = Handling of scientific dishonesty in the Nordic countries. National Committees on Scientific Dishonesty in the Nordic Countries | journal = Lancet | volume = 354 | issue = 9172 | pages = 57–61 | date = July 1999 | pmid = 10406378 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(98)07133-5 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Coping with fraud |work=The COPE Report 1999 |pages=11–18 |url=http://www.publicationethics.org.uk/reports/1999/1999pdf3.pdf |format=PDF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928151119/http://www.publicationethics.org.uk/reports/1999/1999pdf3.pdf |quote=It is 10 years, to the month, since Stephen Lock ... |archive-date=2007-09-28 |access-date=2006-09-02|ref=COPE1999PDF}}</ref>
A 2009 [[systematic review]] and [[meta-analysis]] of survey data found that about 2% of scientists admitted to falsifying, fabricating, or modifying data at least once.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fanelli D | title = How many scientists fabricate and falsify research? A systematic review and meta-analysis of survey data | journal = PLOS One | volume = 4 | issue = 5 | page = e5738 | date = May 2009 | pmid = 19478950 | pmc = 2685008 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0005738 }}</ref> {{dynamic list}}
== Biomedical sciences == * Anna Ahimastos-Lamberti (Australia), a former medical researcher, admitted to fabricating scientific results published in numerous major international medical journals.<ref>{{cite web |title=High-profile researcher made up scientific results |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-09-17/high-profile-researcher-admits-to-fabricating-scientific-results/6781958 |website=ABC News |accessdate=27 September 2018 |language=en-AU |date=17 September 2015}}</ref> As a result, two journal articles about a three-year clinical trial involving a medication used to treat hypertension were retracted.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Phillips |first1=Nicky |title=Blood pressure research by scientist Anna Ahimastos retracted over faked data |url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/blood-pressure-research-by-scientist-anna-ahimastos-retracted-over-faked-data-20150917-gjoqh0.html |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=27 September 2018 |language=en |date=17 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Australian scientist fabricated data |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-34275648 |website=BBC News |accessdate=27 September 2018 |date=17 September 2015}}</ref> * [[Bharat Aggarwal]] (US), a former Ransom Horne, Jr. Distinguished Professor of Cancer Research at the [[University of Texas MD Anderson Cancer Center]],<ref>{{cite web | title = MD Anderson’s Bharat Aggarwal threatens to sue Retraction Watch |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2013/04/10/md-andersons-bharat-aggarwal-threatens-to-sue-retraction-watch/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2013-04-10|access-date=2018-04-12}}</ref> resigned his position after fraud was discovered in 65 papers published by him in the area of [[curcumin]] as a treatment for cancer.<ref>{{cite web | title = M.D. Anderson professor under fraud probe | url = http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/M-D-Anderson-professor-under-fraud-probe-3360037.phpV | work = Chiron }}</ref> Aggarwal has had 28 of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = Cancer journals retract 10 papers, flag 8 more, and apologize for the delay |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/09/04/cancer-journals-retract-10-papers-flag-8-more-and-apologize-for-the-delay/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-09-04|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref> * [[Elias Alsabti]] (Iraq, US), was a medical practitioner who posed as a biomedical researcher. He plagiarized as many as 60 papers in the field of cancer research, many with non-existent co-authors.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Broad WJ | title = Would-be academician pirates papers | journal = Science | volume = 208 | issue = 4451 | pages = 1438–40 | date = June 1980 | pmid = 17796686 | doi = 10.1126/science.208.4451.1438 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Woolf P | title = Fraud in science: how much, how serious? | journal = The Hastings Center Report | volume = 11 | issue = 5 | pages = 9–14 | date = October 1981 | pmid = 7309502 | doi = 10.2307/3561291 | jstor = 3561291 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Miller|first=David | name-list-format = vanc |title=Research Fraud in the Behavioral and Biomedical Sciences|date=1992|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=Hoboken, NJ|isbn=978-0471520689|page=80|chapter=Plagiarism: The Case of Elias A.K. Alsbati}}</ref> * Piero Anversa (US, Italy) and [[Annarosa Leri]] (US, Italy), collaborators and former researchers at Harvard University, were found in a 2014 investigation to have "manipulated and falsified" data in their research on [[Endogenous cardiac stem cell|endogenous cardiac stem cells]], and to have included "false scientific information" in grant applications.<ref>{{cite web | title = Partners Healthcare and Brigham and Women’s Hospital Agree to Pay $10 Million to Resolve Research Fraud Allegations |url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-ma/pr/partners-healthcare-and-brigham-and-women-s-hospital-agree-pay-10-million-resolve|publisher=United States department of Justice|date=2017-04-27|access-date=2018-03-19}}</ref> Anversa and Leri lost a lawsuit they brought against Harvard that claimed the investigation had damaged their reputations.<ref>{{cite web | title = Judge dismisses cardiac stem cell researchers’ lawsuit against Harvard |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2015/07/29/judge-dismisses-cardiac-stem-cell-researchers-lawsuit-against-harvard/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2015-07-29|access-date=2018-03-19}}</ref> Anversa and Leri have one retracted and eight corrected publications.<ref>{{cite web | title = Stem cell researchers investigated for misconduct recommended for roles at Italy’s NIH |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/03/14/stem-cell-researchers-investigated-for-misconduct-recommended-for-roles-at-italys-nih/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-03-14|access-date=2018-03-19}}</ref> In October 2018, Harvard University and Brigham and Women's Hospital called for an additional 31 paper retractions after many failed replications of their work.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/15/health/piero-anversa-fraud-retractions.html|title=Harvard Calls for Retraction of Dozens of Studies by Noted Cardiologist|access-date=2018-10-16|language=en}}</ref> * Edward Awh and graduate student David Anderson (US), formerly of the [[University of Oregon]], retracted nine of their publications due to data fabrication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/education/index.ssf/2015/07/uo_grad_student_falsified_rese.html |title=Feds find UO grad student falsified research data, voiding results of four studies; The Oregonian |publisher=oreganlive.com |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://retractionwatch.com/2016/04/19/two-more-retractions-bring-total-to-9-for-neuroscience-duo/ |title=Two more retractions bring total to 9 for neuroscience duo; Retraction Watch |publisher=retractionwatch.com |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref> This included an action identified by [[The Scientist (magazine)]] as a Top 10 Retraction of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/44895/title/The-Top-10-Retractions-of-2015/ |title=The Top 10 Retractions of 2015; The Scientist |publisher=the-scientist.com |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref> * Werner Bezwoda (South Africa), formerly of the [[University of Witwatersrand]], admitted to scientific misconduct in trials on [[HDC/BMT|high-dose chemotherapy on breast cancer]], stating that he had "committed a serious breach of scientific honesty and integrity."<ref name=pmid10768448>{{cite journal | vauthors = Weiss RB, Rifkin RM, Stewart FM, Theriault RL, Williams LA, Herman AA, Beveridge RA | title = High-dose chemotherapy for high-risk primary breast cancer: an on-site review of the Bezwoda study | journal = Lancet | volume = 355 | issue = 9208 | pages = 999–1003 | date = March 2000 | pmid = 10768448 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(00)90024-2 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Breast Cancer Researcher Admits Falsifying Data |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/02/05/us/breast-cancer-researcher-admits-falsifying-data.html|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=2000-02-05|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Key Breast Cancer Study Was a Fraud |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/apr/27/news/mn-56336|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=2001-04-27|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> * Philippe Bois (US), a former postdoctoral fellow in biochemistry at [[St. Jude Children’s Research Hospital]] was found by the [[United States Office of Research Integrity|Office of Research Integrity]] to have used misleading data for one image in a 2005 ''[[Journal of Cell Biology]]'' paper and completely faked another image in a ''[[Molecular and Cellular Biology]]'' article published the same year. The JCB paper was retracted later in May 2007 and the MCB paper was corrected.<ref>{{cite web | title = St. Jude postdoc faked images: A former postdoctoral researcher at St. Jude Children’s Research Hospital fudged images published in two papers, one of which has since been retracted.|url=