/www.nytimes.com/1989/07/12/us/question-of-scientific-fakery-is-raised-in-inquiry.html|title=Question of scientific fakery is raised in inquiry|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1989-07-12|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> with NIH later stripping Bridges' of his funding.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/pdf/10.1021/cen-v067n032.p024|title=NIH panel strips researcher of funding after plagiarism review|journal=Chemical & Engineering News|volume=67|issue=32|page=24|publisher=American Chemical Society|date=1989-08-07|access-date=2018-04-18|doi=10.1021/cen-v067n032.p024|last1=Zurer|first1=Pamela S}}</ref> * [[Silvia Bulfone-Paus]] (Germany, UK), an immunologist at the [[Research Center Borstel]] and the [[University of Manchester]], has had 13 of her publications retracted following investigations of alleged scientific misconduct involving image manipulation.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/news.2010.671 |title=German research centre widens misconduct probe |journal=Nature |year=2010 |last1=Schiermeier |first1=Quirin | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Marcus|first=Adam | name-list-format = vanc |title=Bulfone-Paus retraction count grows to 13 with one in Transplantation|url=http://retractionwatch.wordpress.com/2011/12/13/bulfone-paus-retraction-count-grows-to-13-with-one-in-transplantation/|work=Retraction Watch|publisher=Retraction Watch|access-date=17 January 2012}}</ref> * [[Ranjit Chandra]] (Canada), former nutrition researcher at [[Memorial University of Newfoundland]] and self-proclaimed "father of nutritional immunology,"<ref>{{cite web | title = Who is Ranjit Kumar Chandra? A timeline of notoriety | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2016/07/26/who-is-ranjit-kumar-chandra-a-timeline-of-notoriety/|date=2016-07-26|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> was in 2015 stripped of his [[Order of Canada]] membership following accusations of scientific wrongdoing in his research.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disgraced researcher Ranjit Chandra stripped of 1989 Order of Canada|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/disgraced-researcher-ranjit-chandra-stripped-of-1989-order-of-canada/article28084791/|access-date=9 January 2016}}</ref> In 2015 Chandra lost a $132 million case against the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]], which in 2006 presented a documentary in which 10 of Chandra's publications were identified as “fraudulent or highly suspicious;”<ref>{{cite web | title = Nutrition researcher Chandra loses libel case against CBC |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2015/07/31/nutrition-researcher-chandra-loses-libel-case-against-cbc/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2015-07-31|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> Chandra was ordered to pay the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] $1.6 million to cover the defendant's legal fees.<ref>{{cite web | title = Ranjit Chandra ordered to pay $1.6M to cover CBC's legal fees in libel lawsuit |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/chandra-paying-legal-fees-1.3322284|publisher=CBC/Radio Canada|date=2015-11-17|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> At least four of Chandra's publications have been retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = Nutrition researcher loses two more papers after misconduct findings come to light | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2016/06/16/nutrition-researcher-loses-two-more-papers-after-misconduct-findings-come-to-light/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2016-06-16|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> * [[Ching-Shih Chen]] (US), the former chair of cancer research at [[The Ohio State University]], was investigated by OSU and the federal Office of Research Integrity after being anonymously reported for falsifying data. The investigation found that he falsified information in at least 11 publications, and that he did not keep any laboratory notebooks on his research, a violation of federal research policies.<ref>{{cite web|title=OSU Professor Falsified Data on Eight Papers, Resigns|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/52212/title/OSU-Professor-Falsified-Data-on-Eight-Papers--Resigns/|website=The Scientist}}</ref><ref name=lantern>{{cite web|title=Ohio State researcher forced to resign after falsifying data in cancer research projects paid for in part by Pelotonia and Stefanie Spielman cancer fund|url=https://www.thelantern.com/2018/03/ohio-state-researcher-forced-to-resign-after-falsifying-data-in-cancer-research-projects-paid-for-in-part-by-pelotonia-and-stefanie-spielman-cancer-fund/|website=The Lantern}}</ref> * [[Carlo M. Croce]] (US), an oncologist and professor of medicine at [[Ohio State University]], has been the subject of several allegations of scientific misconduct, including data falsification, and related institutional investigations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Years of Ethics Charges, but Star Cancer Researcher Gets a Pass|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/08/science/cancer-carlo-croce.html|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=2017-03-08|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Why The Ohio State University decided to go public about misconduct|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2018/04/why-ohio-state-university-decided-go-public-about-misconduct|publisher=American Association for the Advancement of Science|date=2018-04-05|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Carlo Croce, facing misconduct allegations, accuses former colleague of misconduct|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2017/11/09/carlo-croce-facing-misconduct-allegations-accuses-former-colleague-misconduct/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2017-11-09|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> Croce, who has filed lawsuits against critics,<ref>{{cite web|title=Cancer Researcher Calls NY Times Profile Defamatory|url=https://www.courthousenews.com/cancer-researcher-says-ny-times-profile-defamatory/|publisher=Courthouse News Service|date=2017-05-11|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> including a defamation lawsuit against [[David Sanders (biologist)]] of [[Purdue University]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Croce v. Sanders|url=https://www.pacermonitor.com/public/case/21205255/Croce_v_Sanders|publisher=PacerMonitor LLC|date=2017-04-20|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> and a defamation claim against [[The New York Times]] that in 2018 was largely dismissed,<ref>{{cite web|title=Judge Tosses Researcher’s Libel Claims Against NY Times|url=https://www.courthousenews.com/judge-tosses-researchers-libel-claims-against-ny-times/|publisher=Courthouse News Service|date=2018-11-07|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> has had eight of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Probe into Carlo Croce reached "defensible and reasonable" decisions, says external review|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/03/05/probe-into-carlo-croce-reached-defensible-and-reasonable-decisions-says-external-review/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-03-05|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> * [[John Darsee]] (US), a cardiologist formerly based at [[Harvard University]], fabricated data in published research articles and more than 100 abstracts and book chapters.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Stewart WW, Feder N | title = The integrity of the scientific literature | journal = Nature | volume = 325 | issue = 6101 | pages = 207–14 | year = 1987 | pmid = 3808019 | doi = 10.1038/325207a0 | bibcode = 1987Natur.325..207S }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Harvard Suspends Doctor For Fraud |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/12/16/us/harvard-suspends-doctor-for-fraud.html |publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1981-12-16|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> In 1983 Darsee was disbarred for ten years by the US [[National Institutes of Health]].<ref>{{cite web | title = U.S. to Penalize Heart Researcher on Fraudulent Project at Harvard |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/02/16/us/us-to-penalize-heart-researcher-on-fraudulent-project-at-harvard.html|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1983-02-16|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> Darsee has had at least 17 of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://retractionwatch.