are |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/342/bmj.d22|publisher=BMJ Publishing Group Ltd.|date=2011-01-06|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> and the 1998 paper originally presenting his theory was retracted in 2010 by ''The Lancet''.<ref>{{cite web | title = RETRACTED: Ileal-lymphoid-nodular hyperplasia, non-specific colitis, and pervasive developmental disorder in children | url = http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736%2897%2911096-0/abstract|publisher=Elsevier Limited|date=2010-02-02|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Lancet retracts Wakefield’s MMR paper | url = https://www.bmj.com/content/340/bmj.c696 | publisher = BMJ Publishing Group Ltd.|date=2010-02-02|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> Wakefield was unsuccessful in an attempt to sue detractors/critics for libel and defamation.<ref>{{cite web | title = Wakefield Libel Suit Rejected | url = https://www.medpagetoday.com/publichealthpolicy/ethics/34071 |publisher=MedPage Today LLC|date=2012-08-06|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Texas judge throws out Wakefield’s libel action against BMJ | url = https://www.bmj.com/content/345/bmj.e5328 | publisher=BMJ Publishing Group Ltd.|date=2012-08-06|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> * Weishui Y. Weiser (US), a former Assistant Professor of Medicine at [[Harvard Medical School]], falsified data supported by two [[Public Health Service]] (PHS) grants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/notice-files/not95-262.html |title=Nih Guide: Findings Of Scientific Misconduct |publisher=Grants.nih.gov |date= |access-date=2013-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Pravda |first=Douglas M. | name-list-format = vanc |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1995/12/12/nih-cites-two-researchers-for-misconduct/ |title=NIH Cites Two Researchers For Misconduct &#124; The Harvard Crimson |publisher=Thecrimson.com |date= |access-date=2013-03-01}}</ref> Weiser has had at least four publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = ORI findings lead to two retractions — nearly 17 years later | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2012/09/10/ori-findings-lead-to-two-retractions-nearly-17-years-later/ | publisher = Retraction Watch|date=2012-09-10|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> * [[Industrial Bio-Test Laboratories]] fabricated research data to the extent that upon FDA analysis of 867 studies, 618 (71%) were deemed invalid, including many of which were used to gain regulatory approval for widely used household and industrial products.<ref name='JDC essay'>{{cite web | url = http://www.westgard.com/guest16.htm | title = Good Laboratory Practice versus CLIA | access-date = 2012-07-12 | last = Cook | first = Janine Denis | work = University of Maryland, Baltimore}}</ref><ref name='Schneider 1983-05-11 (b)'>{{cite news | first = Keith | last = Schneider | name-list-format = vanc | title = IBT Labs' trial reveals faked data | date = 1983-05-11 | url = http://www.unz.org/Pub/InTheseTimes-1983may11-00003 | work = In These Times | pages = 3, 6 | access-date = 2012-07-16}}</ref> * Researchers at [[St. Jude Children’s Research Hospital]] retracted a 2012 paper published in ''[[Surgery]]'' in 2016 after an internal investigation determined that an image used in the paper was fabricated. The investigation was sparked by other scientists who questioned the paper’s claim to have presented the molecular underpinnings of how a form of [[curcumin]] could reduce the growth of [[neuroblastoma]].<ref>{{cite web | title =St. Jude investigation finds faked data in brain tumor paper|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2015/11/09/investigation-at-st-jude-finds-faked-data-in-surgery-paper/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2015-11-09|access-date=2018-07-10}}</ref> The official retraction stated, “The irregularities in Figure 3E have been investigated by the co-authors and [[St. Jude Children’s Research Hospital]], and the investigation concluded that the image was fabricated. We therefore retract the publication.”<ref>{{cite web | title =Retraction notice to "Liposome-encapsulated curcumin suppresses neuroblastoma growth through nuclear factor-κB inhibition"|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0039606015009034/|publisher=Surgery|date=February 2016|access-date=2018-07-10}}</ref>
