 of Pure and Applied Mathematics}}</ref> The HIT administration's handling of Spivak's misconduct received harsh criticism in Israel<ref>{{cite news |title=Lies of Educators |author=Tali Heruti-Sover |url=http://blogs.haaretz.co.il/taliherutisover/2124/ |newspaper=[[Haaretz]] |date=2014-09-03}}</ref> and abroad.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ferguson|first=Cat|title=Blatant plagiarism sinks paper (and earns a sabbatical!) for mathematician|url=http://retractionwatch.com/2014/10/07/blatant-plagiarism-sinks-paper-and-earns-a-sabbatical-for-mathematician/|work=Retraction Watch}}</ref> In May 2015, another paper by Spivak was retracted for duplication.<ref>{{Cite conference |url=http://lib.amcl.tuc.gr/handle/triton/73 |title=Successive approximations for optimal control in some nonlinear systems with small parameter (RETRACTED Article)|author=A. Spivak (2014) | pages=256–59 |booktitle=Proceedings of the 6th International Conference on Numerical Analysis |isbn= 978-9608475229}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Katsnelson|first=Alla|title=Duplication of "a major part of text and results" adds up to third retraction for mathematician |url=http://retractionwatch.com/2015/06/23/duplication-of-a-major-part-of-text-and-results-adds-up-to-third-retraction-for-mathematician/|work=Retraction Watch}}</ref> * [[Rusi Taleyarkhan]] (US), a nuclear engineer at [[Purdue University]], was found by a University committee in 2008 to have falsified his research.<ref name="latimes">[http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/nation/la-sci-misconduct19-2008jul19,0,1765099.story Purdue physicist found guilty of misconduct], Los Angeles Times, July 19, 2008, Thomas H. Maugh II</ref>
== Plant biology == * Supachai Lorlowhakarn (Thailand), an official at Thailand’s National Innovation Agency (NIA), plagiarized 80% of his PhD thesis concerning asparagus cultivation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20120818084937660|title=Plagiarism controversy raises questions over academic integrity|website=www.universityworldnews.com|access-date=2017-12-03}}</ref> Lorlowhakarn was in 2012 found guilty of criminal forgery, had his PhD degree retracted, was fined, and received a six-month suspended jail sentence, but was not dismissed from NIA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20120825150255758|title=Plagiarism scandal continues after forgery verdict |website=www.universityworldnews.com|access-date=2017-12-03}}</ref> The [[whistleblower]] (and plagiarized author) in this case, [[United Nations]] official Wyn Ellis, was in 2015 detained by Thai immigration officials for four days, apparently due to an official letter from Lorlowhakarn characterizing Ellis as a "danger to Thai society."<ref>{{cite web|title=Whistleblower released after being held for 4 days in Bangkok airport|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2015/09/08/whistleblower-released-after-being-held-for-4-days-in-bangkok-airport/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2015-09-08|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> * [[Olivier Voinnet]] (France) was suspended in 2015 for two years from the [[CNRS]] (the [[French National Centre for Scientific Research]]) due to multiple cases of data manipulation.<ref name="cnrs_investigation">{{cite web|url=http://www2.cnrs.fr/en/2593.htm|title=Completion of the procedure against Olivier Voinnet|author=Press release|work=cnrs.fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed?term=(Voinnet%20O%5BAuthor%5D)%20AND%20%22retracted%20publication%22%5BPublication%20Type%5D|title=PubMed search; Voinnet and retractions}}</ref> In 2016 [[EMBO]] recalled the Gold Medal awarded to Voinnet in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://retractionwatch.com/2016/01/28/embo-takes-back-voinnets-award-investigates-other-awardee-who-just-lost-a-nature-genetics-paper/|title=EMBO takes back Voinnet's award, investigates other awardee who just lost a Nature Genetics paper|work=retractionwatch.com|deadurl=yes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315083319/http://retractionwatch.com/2016/01/28/embo-takes-back-voinnets-award-investigates-other-awardee-who-just-lost-a-nature-genetics-paper/|archive-date=2016-03-15|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/45183/title/Funding-Ban-for-Plant-Biologist/|title=Funding Ban for Plant Biologist|work=the-scientist.com}}</ref> Voinnet has had eight research publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = Caught Our Notice: Voinnet co-author issues another correction |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/03/16/caught-our-notice-voinnet-co-author-issues-another-correction/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-03-16|access-date=2018-03-20}}</ref>
== Social sciences == * [[Mart Bax]] (Netherlands), former professor of political anthropology at the [[Vrije Universiteit]], committed multiple acts of scientific misconduct including data fabrication.<ref>[http://www.vu.nl/nl/nieuws-agenda/nieuws/2013/apr-jun/commissie-baud-onderzoekt-beschuldiging-wetenschapsfraude.asp "Commissie-Baud onderzoekt beschuldiging wetenschapsfraude"]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. VU nieuws, April 29, 2013.</ref><ref>Michiel Baud, Susan Legêne, and Peter Pels (September 9, 2013). [http://www.vu.nl/nl/Images/20130910_RapportBax_tcm9-356928.pdf "Draaien om de werkelijkheid: Rapport over het antropologisch werk van prof. em. M.M.G. Bax"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928122206/http://www.vu.nl/nl/Images/20130910_RapportBax_tcm9-356928.pdf |date=2013-09-28 }}.</ref><ref>[http://www.vu.nl/nl/nieuws-agenda/nieuws/2013/jul-sep/College-van-Bestuur-VU-onderschrijft-conclusies-onderzoekscommissie-Baud.asp "College van Bestuur VU onderschrijft conclusies onderzoekscommissie Baud"]. VU nieuws, September 23, 2013.</ref> Bax, who has had two of his publications retracted, was found in 2013 to have never published 61 of the papers he listed on his CV.<ref>{{cite web|title=Second retraction appears for Mart Bax|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2014/12/29/second-retraction-appears-mart-bax/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2014-12-29|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dutch anthropologist Mart Bax faked 61 papers, says university|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2013/09/23/dutch-anthropologist-mart-bax-faked-61-papers-says-university/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2013-09-23|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> * [[Ward Churchill]] (US), former professor of ethnic studies at [[University of Colorado]], was accused by a University committee of multiple counts of plagiarism, fabrication, and falsification.<ref name="misconduct_report">{{Cite journal | title = Report On Professor Ward Churchill Presented To Media | first1 = Marianne | last1 = Wesson | first2 = Robert | last2 = Clinton | first3 = José | last3 = Limón | first4 = Marjorie | last4 = McIntosh | first5 = Michael | last5 = Radelet | date = May 15, 2006 | publisher = University of Colorado at Boulder | url = https://www.colorado.edu/today/2006/05/15/report-professor-ward-churchill-presented-media | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title =Churchill Verdict Rendered | work = colorado.edu | url =https://www.colorado.edu/coloradan/2009/06/01/churchill-verdict-rendered | access-date=2018-07-30 }}</ref> After the University Chancellor recommended Churchill's dismissal to the Board of Regents, Churchill was in 2009 deemed by a jury to have been wrongly fired, although the presiding judge declined to reinstate him.<ref name="wrongly fired">[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/03/us/03churchill.html?hp&_r=0 Jury Says Professor Was Wrongly Fired]; ''New York Times''; Kirk Johnson and Katherine Q. Seelye; April 2, 2009</ref> In 2010 the Colorado State Court of Appeals upheld the judge's decision to not reinstate Churchill, a decision that in 2012 was upheld by the Colorado Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fired Colorado professor Ward Churchill loses Supreme Court appeal|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2012/09/10/fired-colorado-professor-ward-churchill-loses-supreme-court-appeal/|author=Cotton, Anthony|publisher=Digital First Media|date=2012-09-10|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> In 2013 the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] declined to hear Churchill's appeal of the Colorado Supreme Court decision.<ref>{{cite web|title=Final Loss for Ward Churchill|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2013/04/02/supreme-court-rejects-appeal-ward-churchill|author=Jaschik, Scott|publisher=Inside Higher Ed|date=2013-04-02|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> * Jens Förster (Netherlands, Germany), a social psychologist formerly of the [[University of Amsterdam]] and the [[Ruhr-Universität Bochum]], fabricated data reported in a number of published papers. An investigating committee in 2015 identified in Förster's work data that were "practically impossible" and displayed "strong evidence for low veracity."<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.aab2519 |title=Social psychologist relinquishes chair after data manipulation charges |journal=Science |year=2015 |last1=Van Kolfschooten |first1=Frank }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.aac6776 |title=Report further incriminates social psychologist Jens Förster |journal=Science |year=2015 |last1=Van Kolfschooten |first1=Frank }}</ref> Förster has had three of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Journal adds concern notice to paper by psychologist Jens Förster|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2017/09/29/journal-adds-concern-notice-paper-psychologist-jens-forster//|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2017-09-29|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=University requests 4th retraction for psychologist under fire|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2017/12/15/university-requests-4th-retraction-psychologist-fire/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2017-12-15|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> * [[Bruno Frey]] (Switzerland), an economist formerly at the [[University of Zurich]], in 2010-11 committed multiple acts of [[self-plagiarism]] in articles about the [[Titanic disaster|''Titanic'' disaster]]. Frey admitted to the self-plagiarism, terming the acts "grave mistake[s]" and "deplorable."<ref name="WSJ">{{cite news| url=https://blogs.wsj.com/ideas-market/2011/07/13/economist-slammed-for-concurrent-publications/ | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Christopher | last=Shea | title=Economist Slammed for ‘Concurrent Publications' | date=13 July 2011}}</ref><ref name="AEAweb">{{cite journal |doi=10.1257/jep.25.3.239 |title=Correspondence |journal=Journal of Economic Perspectives |volume=25 |issue=3 |page=239 |year=2011 }}</ref> * [[Michael LaCour]] (US), former graduate student in political science at [[UCLA]], was the lead author of the 2014 article [[When contact changes minds]]. Published in ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'' and making international headlines, the paper was later retracted because of numerous irregularities in the methodology and falsified data.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://stanford.edu/~dbroock/broockman_kalla_aronow_lg_irregularities.pdf | title=Irregularities in LaCour (2014) | date=19 May 2015 | access-date=30 May 2015 | author=Broockman, David, Kalla, Joshua, and Aronow, Peter}}</ref><ref>http://retractionwatch.com/2015/06/18/if-you-think-its-rude-to-ask-to-look-at-your-co-authors-data-youre-not-doing-science-guest-post/</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/29/science/journal-science-retracts-study-on-gay-canvassers-and-same-sex-marriage.html | title=Journal Retracts Study on Changing Attitudes on Same-Sex Marriage | work=New York Times | date=28 May 2015 | access-date=28 May 2015 | author=Carey, Benedict}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.aac4659 |title=Science retracts gay marriage paper without agreement of lead author La ''Cour'' |journal=Science |year=2015 |last1=Bohannon |first1=John }}</ref> Following the retraction [[Princeton University]] rescinded an assistant professorship that had been offered to LaCour.<ref>{{cite web|title=U. revokes hire offer after allegations of publishing falsified data|url=http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/article/2015/06/u-revokes-hire-offer-after-allegations-of-publishing-falsified-data/|publisher=The Daily Princetonian|date=2015-07-29|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> * Elisabeth Nixon (US), a former student at [[Ohio State University]], had her PhD in anthropology revoked due to plagiarism.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.courthousenews.com/2010/08/26/29882.htm | title=AProfessor Says Another Prof Plagiarized | work=Courthouse News | date=August 26, 2010 | access-date=May 1, 2014 | author=Koeninger, Kevin}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/local/2010/09/15/plagiarism-a-persistent-problem-on-campuses.html | title= Plagiarism a persistent problem on campuses | work=Columbus Dispatch | date=September 15, 2010 | access-date=May 1, 2014 | author=Pyle, Encarnacion}}</ref> * Karen M. Ruggiero (US), former Assistant Professor of Psychology at [[Harvard University]], fabricated NIH-sponsored research data on gender and discrimination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/notice-files/NOT-OD-02-020.html |title=Nih Guide: Findings Of Scientific Misconduct |publisher=[[United States Department of Health and Human Services]] |date=2001-12-13 |quote=Notice: NOT-OD-02-020 |access-date=2009-09-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |url=http://www.apa.org/monitor/feb02/fraud.html |title=Research fraud needn't happen at all |author=Bridget Murray |journal=Monitor on Psychology |publisher=[[American Psychological Association]] |volume=33 |issue=2 |date = February 2002|access-date=2009-09-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albany.edu/~scifraud/data/sci_fraud_4555.html |title=\Jacobson, Jennifer. "A Psychology Professor Resigns Amid Accusations of Research Fraud at |publisher=Albany.edu |date=2001-08-10 |access-date=2013-03-01}}</ref> * [[Diederik Stapel]] (Netherlands), former professor of social psychology at [[Tilburg University]], fabricated data in dozens of studies on human behaviour,<ref>{{cite news |author=Gretchen Vogel |title=Dutch 'Lord of the Data' Forged Dozens of Studies |magazine=[[Science (magazine)|Science]] |url=http://news.sciencemag.org/scienceinsider/2011/10/report-dutch-lord-of-the-data-fo.html?ref=hp |date=31 October 2011 |access-date=2 November 2011 |deadurl=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111103090859/http://news.sciencemag.org/scienceinsider/2011/10/report-dutch-lord-of-the-data-fo.html?ref=hp |archive-date=3 November 2011 |df= }}</ref> a deception described by the [[New York Times]] as "an audacious academic fraud."<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/28/magazine/diederik-stapels-audacious-academic-fraud.html?pagewanted=1&_r=1&&pagewanted=all The Mind of a Con Man: Diederik Stapel, a Dutch social psychologist, perpetrated an audacious academic fraud by making up studies that told the world what it wanted to hear about human nature.], NY Times, published April 26, 2013.</ref> Stapel has had 58 of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Diederik Stapel now has 58 retractions|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2015/12/08/diederik-stapel-now-has-58-retractions/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2015-12-08|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> * [[Brian Wansink]] (US), former John S. Dyson Endowed Chair in the Applied Economics and Management Department at [[Cornell University]], was found in 2018 by a University investigatory committee to have "committed academic misconduct in his research and scholarship, including misreporting of research data, problematic statistical techniques, failure to properly document and preserve research results, and inappropriate authorship."<ref>{{cite web|title=Cornell finds that food marketing researcher Brian Wansink committed misconduct, as he announces retirement|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/09/20/beleaguered-food-marketing-researcher-brian-wansink-announces-his-retirement-from-cornell/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-09-20|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=A Prominent Researcher on Eating Habits Resigned After a Scandal Over His Studies|url=http://time.com/5402927/brian-wansink-cornell-resigned/|publisher=Time Inc.|date=2018-09-21|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=This Ivy League food scientist was a media darling. He just submitted his resignation, the school says.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2018/09/20/this-ivy-league-food-scientist-was-media-darling-now-his-studies-are-being-retracted/?utm_term=.13eb37dc3222|publisher=The Washington Post|date=2018-09-20|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref> Wansink has had 13 of his papers retracted, and at least 15 others have been corrected.<ref>{{cite web|title=JAMA journals retract six papers by food marketing researcher Brian Wansink|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/09/19/jama-journals-retract-six-papers-by-food-marketing-researcher-brian-wansink/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-09-19|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref>
== Other == * In 2016 the scientific publisher [[Springer Nature]] retracted 58 papers from seven journals, authored mostly by [[Iran]]-based researchers, because the papers showed evidence of authorship manipulation, peer-review manipulation, and/or plagiarism.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nature.2016.20916 |title=Publisher pulls 58 articles by Iranian scientists over authorship manipulation |journal=Nature |year=2016 |last1=Callaway |first1=Ewen }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Springer, BMC retracting nearly 60 papers for fake reviews and other issues|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2016/11/01/springer-bmc-retracting-nearly-60-papers-for-fake-reviews-and-other-issues/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2016-11-01|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref> * [[Ohio University]] in 2006 alleged more than three dozen cases of plagiarism in master's degree theses dating back 20 years in its mechanical engineering department.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ohio College Stung by Plagiarism Charges|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/21/AR2006082100068.html|publisher=The Washington Post|date=2006-08-21|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> A former faculty member involved in the plagiarism cases, Jay S. Gunasekera, was removed from his position as department chair, had his title of "distinguished professor" rescinded,<ref>{{cite web|title='Distinguished' No Longer|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2008/02/22/ohio|publisher=Inside Higher Ed|date=2008-02-22|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> and in 2011 settled a lawsuit he had brought against the University.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ohio University professor Jay Gunasekera settles lawsuit over his role in plagiarism scandal|url=https://www.academicjobs.net/news-1200-Ohio_University_professor_Jay_Gunasekera_settles_lawsuit_over_his_role_in_plagiarism_scandal.html|publisher=Academic Jobs|date=2011-03-09|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> Another former faculty member implicated in the plagiarism cases, Bhavin Mehta, in 2012 lost a defamation suit he had brought against the University.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mehta v. Ohio Univ., 2012 Ohio 3677|url=https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/2694786/mehta-v-ohio-univ/|publisher=CourtListener|date=2012-03-06|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> * 486 Chinese cancer researchers were found guilty of engaging in a fraudulent peer-review scheme by China’s [[Ministry of Science and Technology]]. The investigation was initiated after the retraction of 107 papers published in [[Tumor Biology]] between 2012 and 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peer-Review Fraud Scheme Uncovered in China|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/49998/title/Peer-Review-Fraud-Scheme-Uncovered-in-China/|website=The Scientist}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nearly 500 researchers guilty of misconduct, says Chinese gov’t investigation|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2017/07/31/nearly-500-researchers-guilty-misconduct-says-chinese-govt-investigation/|website=Retraction Watch|date=31 July 2017}}</ref> This is reported to be the most papers retracted from one journal.<ref>{{cite web|title=A new record: Major publisher retracting more than 100 studies from cancer journal over fake peer reviews|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2017/04/20/new-record-major-publisher-retracting-100-studies-cancer-journal-fake-peer-reviews/|website=Retraction Watch|date=20 April 2017}}</ref>
